Note the key result: with 2 platforms full at t=10, train C (duration 10) **waited** and got P2 the instant B departed at 25 → `[25,35)`.

## 8. Key Flow (sequence diagram)

One `assign` call, end to end.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Client
    participant Station
    participant Strategy
    participant Platform
    participant Observer
    Client->>Station: assign(Train C, arr=10, dur=10)
    Station->>Station: reject if duplicate id
    Station->>Strategy: select(platforms, 10, 10)
    Strategy->>Platform: earliestSlot(10,10) for each
    Platform-->>Strategy: P1 returns 30, P2 returns 25
    Strategy-->>Station: choose P2 start=25
    Station->>Platform: add Booking [25,35)
    Station->>Station: index byTrain[C]
    Station->>Observer: onAssigned(booking, waited=true)
    Station-->>Client: Booking C @P2 [25,35)
```

The Station never decides *where* itself — it asks the Strategy, which polls each Platform's earliest slot, then commits the winning booking to both the platform timeline and the train index, and finally fans out to observers.

## 9. Concurrency, Edge Cases & Extensibility

**Concurrency model:** one **lock-guarded shared object** (the Station). A single `ReentrantLock` guards `assign` and both queries, so the **select-then-book** check-then-act is atomic — two concurrent arrivals can't be handed the same slot. It's reentrant in case a guarded method later calls another guarded method.

**Edge cases handled:** zero/negative-length stay (rejected at construction), duplicate train id, out-of-range platform, query on an empty platform (returns null/-1), end-exclusive boundary (platform free exactly at `end`), all-platforms-full (train waits, never dropped), gaps in a platform's timeline (slot-finder fills them).

**Extensibility without rewrites:**
- New assignment policy → new `PlatformSelectionStrategy` (e.g. minimize fragmentation, dedicate platforms to train types).
- New reactions → new `AssignmentObserver` (display board, alerting, metrics).
- Train *types*/priority → add a field to Train and a priority-aware Strategy; nothing else changes.
- Real-time event loop → feed arrivals as they happen; the same `assign` plans the slot.

**Hardest follow-ups this design already answers:** "what if all platforms busy?" (waits via `earliestSlot`); "two trains arrive at once?" (lock makes it atomic); "change the assignment rule?" (Strategy); "platform frees exactly when another arrives?" (half-open interval). A follow-up it would *grow* into: **cancellation/early departure** — add `Platform.remove(booking)` + a `byTrain` cleanup under the same lock.

> 💬 **30-second summary:** "A Station owns N Platforms; each Platform keeps a sorted timeline of Bookings. On assign, the Station delegates to a pluggable Strategy that asks every platform for its earliest free slot and picks the soonest — so a train with no immediate platform simply *waits* and gets the next opening, never gets dropped. Bookings are indexed both by platform and by train, so both time-queries are direct. I used Strategy for the selection policy, Observer for assignment notifications, and a Factory for validated trains, all under a single lock that makes select-and-book atomic. I compiled and ran it — including the waiting case and all the boundary rejections."

