## 1. Requirements & Clarifications

We're designing a **Train Platform Management System**: a station with N platforms assigns each arriving train a platform for its whole stay, makes trains **wait** when everything is full, and answers two **time-based queries**.

**Clarifying questions to ask the interviewer:**
- When a train waits, does it keep its original duration but a later start (slot shifts)? Or is arrival/departure fixed and we reject? → *I'll assume the stay duration is fixed and the start shifts to the earliest free moment ("wait until a platform becomes free").*
- Are arrivals fed in real time (event loop) or as a schedule we plan? → *I'll plan deterministically at assignment time, which works for both.*
- Can a train be assigned more than once? → *No — train ids are unique.*
- Should `[start, end)` be half-open (a platform frees exactly at `end`)? → *Yes, end-exclusive, so the next train can take it at `end`.*

**Assumptions:** time = integer minutes; platforms 1-based; train ids unique; one stay per train.

> 💬 "Before I code, let me lock scope: when all platforms are busy, I'll keep the train's *duration* fixed and slide its start to the earliest time a platform frees — that's the natural reading of 'wait'. I'll treat time windows as half-open so a platform is reusable the instant a train departs. Sound right?"

## 2. Use Cases & Actors

| Actor | Use case |
|---|---|
| Station operator / scheduler | Configure N platforms; assign an arriving train |
| Train | Arrives, occupies a platform for its stay, departs |
| Query client (display board, ops) | "Who is on platform P at time t?" / "Where is train X at time t?" |

Core interactions: **assign(train)** → returns a confirmed booking (immediately or after a wait); **trainAtPlatform(p,t)**; **platformOfTrain(id,t)**.

## 3. Core Entities (Objects)

- **Train** — value object: id, arrival, duration. Validates itself.
- **Booking** — a confirmed reservation: trainId, platform, `[start,end)`. The unit of truth that survives to query time.
- **Platform** — owns its sorted list of bookings; knows its earliest free slot.
- **Station** — the orchestrator: holds platforms, the train→bookings index, the selection strategy, observers, and the lock.
- **PlatformSelectionStrategy** — pluggable rule for *which* platform/slot to pick.
- **AssignmentObserver** — gets notified on each assignment.
- **TrainFactory** — single validated construction point.

> 💬 "I extract nouns from the spec — train, platform, station, booking — then ask which of them *owns behaviour*. Platform owns its timeline; Station owns the global decision. The decision *policy* I deliberately pull out into a Strategy so it's swappable."

## 4. Class Design (diagram)

This shows the structure and relationships.

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class Station {
        -List~Platform~ platforms
        -Map~String,List~ byTrain
        -PlatformSelectionStrategy strategy
        -ReentrantLock lock
        +assign(Train) Booking
        +trainAtPlatform(p, t) String
        +platformOfTrain(id, t) int
        +addObserver(o)
    }
    class Platform {
        +int number
        -List~Booking~ bookings
        +earliestSlot(arrival, dur) int
        +add(Booking)
        +at(t) Booking
    }
    class Booking {
        +String trainId
        +int platform
        +int start
        +int end
        +covers(t) bool
    }
    class Train {
        +String id
        +int arrival
        +int duration
    }
    class PlatformSelectionStrategy {
        <<interface>>
        +select(platforms, arrival, dur) int[]
    }
    class EarliestAvailableStrategy
    class AssignmentObserver {
        <<interface>>
        +onAssigned(Booking, waited)
    }
    class LoggingObserver
    class TrainFactory

    Station o-- Platform : owns
    Station ..> Booking : indexes
    Platform o-- Booking : holds timeline
    Station --> PlatformSelectionStrategy : uses
    PlatformSelectionStrategy <|.. EarliestAvailableStrategy
    Station --> AssignmentObserver : notifies
    AssignmentObserver <|.. LoggingObserver
    TrainFactory ..> Train : creates
```

**Relationships:** Station **composes** Platforms (their lifecycle is the station's). Both Station and Platform reference **Bookings** — Platform stores them as a per-platform timeline, Station indexes the same bookings by train id so query 2 is O(1)-ish. Station **depends on** the Strategy and Observer interfaces, not concrete classes (Dependency Inversion).

## 5. Design Patterns & Principles

- **Strategy** — `PlatformSelectionStrategy` isolates the "which platform/slot" policy. Today `EarliestAvailableStrategy`; tomorrow "lowest-numbered platform" or "balance load" with **zero changes to Station**.
- **Factory** — `TrainFactory` centralizes validated Train construction.
- **Observer** — `AssignmentObserver` lets display boards / loggers / SMS alerts react to assignments without Station knowing about them.
- (Optional) Station could be a **Singleton** per physical station — I left it injectable instead, which is more testable.

**SOLID:** *SRP* — Platform manages a timeline, Station orchestrates, Strategy decides. *OCP* — new policies/observers added without editing Station. *DIP* — Station codes to interfaces. *LSP* — any strategy/observer is substitutable.

> 💬 (layman) "Strategy is just: I don't hard-code *how* I pick a platform — I hand the station a little rulebook it can swap out. Observer is: instead of the station calling the display board directly, the board *subscribes* and gets pinged when something happens — so I can add new listeners without touching the core."

## 6. Implementation — narrated, class by class

**Train** — immutable, self-validating. Stores duration (not departure) because waiting shifts start but keeps duration.

```java
final class Train {
    final String id; final int arrival; final int duration;
    Train(String id, int arrival, int departure) {
        if (id == null || id.isBlank()) throw new IllegalArgumentException("train id required");
        if (departure <= arrival) throw new IllegalArgumentException("departure must be > arrival");
        this.id = id; this.arrival = arrival; this.duration = departure - arrival;
    }
}
```

**Booking** — the confirmed reservation and the unit that survives to query time. `covers(t)` enforces the half-open `[start,end)` rule.

```java
final class Booking {
    final String trainId; final int platform; final int start, end;
    Booking(String trainId, int platform, int start, int end) {
        this.trainId = trainId; this.platform = platform; this.start = start; this.end = end;
    }
    boolean covers(int t) { return t >= start && t < end; }
}
```

**Platform** — owns a list of bookings kept sorted by start. The tricky method is `earliestSlot`: it walks the timeline finding the first gap `>= arrival` big enough for the duration. If the train fits before the next booking, return the candidate; otherwise push the candidate past that booking's end.

```java
final class Platform {
    final int number;
    private final List<Booking> bookings = new ArrayList<>();
    Platform(int number) { this.number = number; }

    int earliestSlot(int arrival, int duration) {
        int candidate = arrival;
        for (Booking b : bookings) {
            if (candidate + duration <= b.start) return candidate; // fits in the gap
            if (b.end > candidate) candidate = b.end;              // shift past this booking
        }
        return candidate;
    }
    void add(Booking b) {
        int i = 0;
        while (i < bookings.size() && bookings.get(i).start < b.start) i++;
        bookings.add(i, b);
    }
    Booking at(int t) { for (Booking b : bookings) if (b.covers(t)) return b; return null; }
}
```

**Strategy** — picks the platform giving the *earliest* start, tie-broken by lowest number.

```java
interface PlatformSelectionStrategy {
    int[] select(List<Platform> platforms, int arrival, int duration);
}
final class EarliestAvailableStrategy implements PlatformSelectionStrategy {
    public int[] select(List<Platform> platforms, int arrival, int duration) {
        int bestPlatform = -1, bestStart = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for (Platform p : platforms) {
            int s = p.earliestSlot(arrival, duration);
            if (s < bestStart) { bestStart = s; bestPlatform = p.number; }
        }
        return new int[]{bestPlatform, bestStart};
    }
}
```

**Station** — the orchestrator. `assign` is the heart: it rejects duplicates, asks the strategy, creates the booking, records it on **both** the platform timeline and the train index, then notifies observers. Every assign reaches a **defined outcome** — a booking, immediate or waited — never a silent drop. The whole method is under a `ReentrantLock` so the check-then-act (select-slot-then-book) is atomic.

```java
final class Station {
    private final List<Platform> platforms = new ArrayList<>();
    private final Map<String, List<Booking>> byTrain = new HashMap<>();
    private final PlatformSelectionStrategy strategy;
    private final List<AssignmentObserver> observers = new ArrayList<>();
    private final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();

    Station(int numPlatforms, PlatformSelectionStrategy strategy) {
        if (numPlatforms <= 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException("need >=1 platform");
        for (int i = 1; i <= numPlatforms; i++) platforms.add(new Platform(i));
        this.strategy = strategy;
    }
    void addObserver(AssignmentObserver o) { observers.add(o); }

    Booking assign(Train train) {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            if (byTrain.containsKey(train.id))
                throw new IllegalStateException("duplicate train id: " + train.id);
            int[] choice = strategy.select(platforms, train.arrival, train.duration);
            int platformNo = choice[0], start = choice[1];
            Platform p = platforms.get(platformNo - 1);
            Booking b = new Booking(train.id, platformNo, start, start + train.duration);
            p.add(b);
            byTrain.computeIfAbsent(train.id, k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(b);
            boolean waited = start > train.arrival;
            for (AssignmentObserver o : observers) o.onAssigned(b, waited);
            return b;
        } finally { lock.unlock(); }
    }
    // queries validate the boundary then read the timeline...
}
```

